{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_broadwick_ver01/data/sn93065779/00279558236/1945112601/0505.xml":{"full_text":"24\nMore Shopping Days\nUntil Christmas\n$2:00 PER YEAR\u2014IN ADVANCE.\nWartime Rationing\nAbout To Come To\nEnd In Lincolnton\n\u2018lke\u2019 for Unification\n(J f nfl\u00df\nGen. Dwight O. Eisenhower Is\nshown with his wife, prior to her\nIllness, as they arrived in Washing\nton where the general supported\nthe army\u2019s plea for a single depart\nment of national defease.\nLOCAL REDCROSS\nWIU BE SALUTED\nThe Lincoln Chapter, American\nRed Cross, will he saluted Mon\nday evening, November 26, 1946, at\n7 o\u2019clock in the first of a series of\nfive broadcasts 0 n the role played by\nNorth Carolina chapters in the Red\nCross program at home and overseas.\nThe broadcast will come from Station\nWAYS at Charlotte, North Carolina.\nThis honor will be rendered to the\nLincoln County Chapter in recogni\ntion of it soutstanding work in\nclaims. The salute to the Lincoln\nchapter will com e at the end of an\ninterview on Red Cross services to\nveterans, in which two other chap-i\nters will also be cited.\nIn referring to the forthcoming\nbroadcast, Mrs. Gordon Goodson, ex\necutive secretary of the Lincoln\nCounty Chapter, emphasized the\nneed of greater numbers of workeis\nin the chapters to carry on the ever\nexpanding service to veterans.\n\u201cEvery day more of our men are\nout of uniform and coming back\nhome,\u201d said Mrs. Goodson, \u201cand it\nis the pleasure and privilege of the\nRed Cross workers in the Lincoln\nCountey chapter to serve them. All\nour ex-servicemen can depend on us\nto give them all the helb possible.\u201d\nMrs. Goodson said that Home Ser\nvice in the Lincoln County chapter\nwas assisting a greater number of\nveterans and their families with many\nof the same problems that were,\nbrought by the servicemen\u2019s families\nwhile the men were in the armed\nforces. I\nThe return of the men, however,\nhad brought in many new circum\nstances, Mrs. Goodson stated.\n\u201cClaims for government benefits\nare very much to the front now, and\nprobably will be for months to come.\nMany a hero who stormed the ene\nmy beachheads beats a retreat wnen\nhe sees a government form. That\u2019s\nwhere our Home Service workers can\nhelp. We also help the man secure\nnecessary documents, and the Red\nCross will represent him with Vet\nerans Administration if he wishes.\n\u201cSometimes a disabled veteran has\nto wait until his claim is decided on.\nWhile he and his family are waiting\nfor that first pension check, Red\nCross often steps in with financial\nassistance. Food, fuel, shelter, emer\ngency medical care \u2014Red Cross helps\nwith all these things.\nLincolnton Girls\nMembers May Court\nMiss Ann, Abernethy, daughter of\nMr. and Mrs. Jas. A. Abernethy, Jr.,\nof this city, and Miss Mabel Ruth\nMundy, daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nJerry Mundy, of Denver, have been\nelectel to the May Court, at Queens\nCollege, Charlotte.\nMiss Abernethy, a member of\nKappa Delta, national social sorority,\nwas a member of the May Court last\nyear. Miss Mundy is president of\nAlpha Eta Sigma, social sorority on\nthe campus. Both girls are mem\nbers of the sophomore class.\nJoe\u2019s Case Serves Soldiers\nFree Thanksgiving Dinner\nJoe Hawkins, who bought the\nJoe\u2019s Case recently from Joe Stamey,\nbegan his management of the place\nin a unique manner. On the day be\nfore Thanksgiving he posted a sign\non the front of the Case inviting ail\nex-service men, nurses And doctors\nfrom World War II to come in and\nhave a free Thanksgiving turkey\ndinner. A number of veterans ac\ncepted the invitation and were loud\nIn their praise of the excellent meal\nThe Lincoln Times\n\nCounty\u2019s Record of Sharing Is\nOne For Citizens to Be\nHappy and Proud Os\nWartime rationing in Lincoln\ncounty is about at the end of its\ntether, but recollection of the point\nsystem of the OPA will linger on for\nat least the duration of the present\ngeneration. There was very little\nthat we wanted, and nothing at all\nthat we needed denied us here, where\nresidents of this community have\nlong been noted for neighborliness\nand generosity.\nOur record of wartime sharing\nrationing was a more popular word\nis a good record and we went through\nthe ration point period as good cit\nizens and good Americans.\nIt was our home boys, from North,\nEast, South and West Lincoln county\nwho really made the great sacrifices\nof war. A number of them made the\nsupreme sacrifice, and those who are\nleturning to the firesides of their\nhomes now can tell us experiences\nthat are strange and unrealistic to\nthose of us wh 0 stayed at home.\nTheir mess kits were empty but our\ncupboards were never bare.\nWe must never forget the hard\nships and suffering endured by Lin\ncoln county\u2019s fighting force. We\nshould always be grateful for the\ncomforts and security they provided\nfor all of us at home.\nAnd in our remembrance let us\nmake it a part of the record that\nLincoln county's war price and ra\ntioning board did an outstanding war\njob that deserves our praise and\nthanks for its patriotism and great 1\ncontribution to the homefront war\neffort.\nLincoln county congratulates Sum\nmey Alexander, chairman of the local\nboard and every member, who often\nwere abused for forcing some of us\nto obey regulations that were set up\nfor the benefit of all.\nThese volunteers worked long hours\nwithout pay. They have earned the\ngratitude of all Lincoln county resi\ndents who believe in fair play. And i\nthat just about covers every man, 1\nwoman and child within our borders.\nSugar rationing will remain with\nus until it is no longer needed. Let\u2019s I\nstir our coffee with a little more\nvigor until this last item goes the 1\nway of other ration points.\nWomen Volunteers\nStill Needed To Do\nRed Cross Knitting\nYes, we still have knitting to be 1\ndoae. The man that was a hero yes- i\nterday, fought without failing for i\nthe freedom we are now enjoying, 1\nwill be the forgotten man today and t\ntomorrow if we fail him now. l\nTre war is over\u2014bet our task is t\nnot finished, and will not be finished\nuntil every able-bodied father broth-\ner and husband returns to civilian 1\nlife; and every war-crippled man is s\ncared for. t\nLadies, you helped the men while t\nthe fighting continued, now let\u2019s com- t\nfort those who so unselfishly gave, t\nand continue to give. 1\nMost of us enjoy a good, warm\nhome, and have plenty of clothing\nto keep us warm when out of doors, t\nBut on the other hand, millions of 1\npeople in the world are cold and hun- 1\ngry today. Let\u2019s knit to keep some-\none warm and happy. 1\nYarn is available and ready for c\nyou at Red Cross headquarters. We j\nhave an urgent call for sweaters and\nsocks. Come by the office or call 1\n182 and the yarn will be delivered 1\nto you. 1\nBIRTH ANNOUNCEMENT i\nBorn to Sgt. and Mrs. James V. S\nMaugerie an eight-pound son on Fri\nday, November 23, at the Gordon\nCrowell Memorial hospital. Mrs.\nMaugeri an eight-pound son on Fri-\nMiss Alma Harrill, of Lincolnton,\nRoute 3.\nVeterans who re-enlist in the Army i\nwithin twenty days after their dis- 1\njcharge may retain their present i\n,Army rating as a permanent rating i\nlin the Regular Army.\nprovided.\nThe new manager announces that\nonly first class cooks will be em\nployed in the case and that prices\nwill be reasonable. No beer will be\nsold and that everyone will be treat\ned with respect while in his place\nof business.\nHe especially invites all G. I. Joe\u2019s\nto patronize the case at any time.\nRead his advertisement on page\ntwo is this issue of The Times.\nPUBLISHED EVERY MONDAY AND THURSDAY\nPresents a Reconversion Program\nk -if\ni 1 '\u25a0'allonal Association of Manufacturer\u2019s reconversion council\nshown as they presented to congress a reconversion program which\nrecommended elimination of wage controls and the removal of OPA\nprice restrictions by February 15, 1946. Left to right: C. B. Randall\nWashington; R. R. Wason, New York City and John Alrey, Ann Arbor.\nTool, Dye Workers\nMay Join In Fight\nOn General Motors\nHenry C. Cashion\nWin* Bronze Star\nWith the Sixth Army in Japan\u2014\nTechnician Fourth Grade Henry C.\nCashion, son of Mrs. Margaret B.\nCashion, rural route, Lincolnton, N.\nC., has been awarded a Bronze Star\nmedal by Major General P. W. Clark\nson, commander of the battle-harden\ned 33rd Division, now occupying the\nKobe-Osaka-Kyoto area in Japan as\npart of General Walter Krueger\u2019s\nSixth Army.\nSgt. Cashion was cited for meri\ntorious service during the Northern\nLuzon campaign, climaxed when the\n33rd captured Baguio, mountain\nstronghold of General Yamashita.\nSgt. Cashhnr came overseas with\nthe \u201cGolden Cross\u201d Division in July,\n1943, to the Central Pacific area and\nlater moved to the Southwest Pacific\narea where he participated in the\nNew Guinea, Morotai and Philippine\nLiberation campaigns. He is entitled\nto wear the Asiatic-Pacific ribbon\nwith two battle stars and the Philip\npine Liberation ribbon with one star.\nFinal Appeal Made\nTo Local Farmers To\n\u201cGet Out And Vote\u201d\nA final appeal to \u201cget out and vote\u201d\nhas been directed to Lincoln county\nfarmers by W. B. Abernethy, chair\nman of the county AAA committee.\nFarmers in 19 communities will ballot\nthis week on the AAA committee\nmen who will represent and assist\nthem during the coming year.\n\u201cA big turnout of voters will dem\nonstrate that Lincoln county farmers\nbelieve in the elected committeemen\nsystem which enables farmers to run\ntheir own farm programs,\u201d Mr. Aber\nnethy said. On the other hand, a small\nturnout might be interpreted to mean\nthat farmers are not interested in\nhaving their programs run by farm\ners.\nWith many reconversion programs\nahead, the AAA committeemen will\nhave heavy responsibilities in 1946.\nThey will b e handling details of Gov\nernment programs and also voicing\nthe opinions of local farmers on rec\nommendations for new or improved\nprograms.\nCommitteeman elections will be\nheld in Lincoln county beginning\nNovember 30th, according to the fol\nlowing schedule:\nRock Springs High School, Nov.\n30th\u20149 to 6.\nIron Station School, Nov. 30th\n9 to 6.\nCourthouse, Lincolnton, Nov. 30th\n-\u20149 to 5.\nHoward\u2019s Creek School, Nov. 30th\n\u20149 to 5.\nNorth Brook No. 2 School, Nov.\n30th\u20149 to 6.\nIt was pointed out that approxi-!\nmately 3,000 farmers are eligible to\nvote in the elections this year. Any\nfarmers who participate in the agri\ncultural conservation, or Federal crop\ninsurance programs may vote.\nFive farmers will be chosen as\ncommitteemen in each community\u2014|\nthree as regular committee members\nand two alternates. Also elected will\nbe a delegate to the county conven\ntion to be held later, where the coun\nty committee of three members will\nbe elected.\nMISS MACIE DUNCAN ENTERS\nSERVICE OFFICERS SCHOOL\nMiss Macie Duncan left Sunday\nfor Chapel Hill where she will at\ntend the Service Officers Training\nSchool. She will be absent from her\noffice in the Courthouse through Fri\nlay, November 30.\n~A~Timea Want Ad WIU SeU It!\nLINCOLNTON, N. C., MONDAY, NOV. 26, 1945\nManagement Sa y a Continu\nance of Dispute Will Force\nLayoff of 100,000 Men\nThe CIO Tool and Die Workers\nmay join in the fight against Gen\neral Motors, a union source said.\nFrom management\u2019s corner over the\nweek-end came an assertion that con\ntinuance of the automotive dispute\nwill force the layoff of 100,000 em\nployes of the automobile parts in\ndustry.\nPickets thrown around General\nMotors Corporation plants in 51\ncities by 176,000 striking CIO United\nAutomobile Workers already had\nkept 25,000 additional GM employes\nfrom work. Union tookesmen said\npicket lines were being enlarged and\npredicted the total Tdle will reach\n248,000 today (Monday), counting\n73,000 salaried employes.\nThe auto workers\u2019 walkout ac\ncounted for the largest single seg\nment of the half-million workers off\ntheir jobs in labor disputes across\nthe country. Otrer big strikes in\nvolved 60,000 AFL lumber and saw\nmill workers in the Pacific North\nwest; 60,000 machinists in San Fran\ncisco, 6,100 employes of the Brown\nand Sharpe Manufacturing Company,\nProvidence, R. 1., and 4,300 Grey\nhound bus drivers in 26 states.\nThe UAW-CIO mak seek the tool\nand die makers\u2019 support in the auto\nworkers\u2019 strike for a 30 per cent\nwage increase, union sources said.\nThese sources said this did not nec\nessarily mean the tool and die men\nwould strike, but rather that they\nwould refuse to work on material for\nGeneral Motors. The tool and die\nworkers\u2019 Detroit local will meet\nTuesday night to talk over the plan.\nFrom Frank Rising, general man\nager of the Automotive and Aviation\nParts Manufacturers' Association,\ncame the statement the parts indus\ntry would have to lay off thousands\nof employees soon because of the loss\nof GM business.\nCHINESEHOLDSIX\nMARINE FLYERS\nShanghai, Nov. 26 \u2014United States\nThird Amphibious Corps officers are\nengaged in negotiations with Chinese\nCommunists for the release of six\nAmerican Marine flyers held prison\ner by the Communists at a remote\nvillage 80 miles west of Tientsin.\nThe flyers were forced down 14\ndays ago during a flight from Peip\ning to Tientsin.\nEfforts to obtain the names of the\nprisoners were unavailing at Marine\nheadquarters but I am informed re\nliably that one pilot is Lieut. R. R.\nHolbrook of Three Rivers, Texas.\nHe was flying a warrant officer,\ntwo sergeants and tw 0 privates, all\nof the First Marine Air wing, to\nTientsin. He became lost and the\nplane ran out of gasoline. All the\nprisoners were reported in good con\ndition.\nI The plane has been spotted on a\nfield, partially camouflaged. Deep\nruts in the field which were made\nby the plane had been plowed over\nin an effort t 0 keep aerial spotters\nfrom finding it.\nBecause of the remoteness of the\nvillage and the condition of the rug\nged country, the negotiations have\nbeen slow. Messengers require sev\neral days to make tre round trip\nfrom the village to Tientsin.\nOfficially the Third Amphibious\nCorps has been silent on the whole\nepisode. It is known, however that\nthe matter has been taken up with\nGeneralissimo Chiarig Kai-shek in\nChungking. Nationalist forces there\nhave contacted Communist represen\ntatives in an effort to obtain release\nof the Americans.\nTEACHER SUPPLY\nIN LINCOLN COUNTY\nNOW INADEQUATE\n'WT\nIt is a long way from the Little\nRed School House with its one teach\ner and the three R\u2019s to the \u201cbig busi\nness\u201d education is today. Last year\n*265,625.24 was invested in the busi\nness of educating nearly 6,000 chil\ndren in Lincoln county.\nThis figure may seem adequate to\na casual reader. However, by the\nprocess of simple arithmetic, one\nfinds that only *44 was spent for\neach child. On the basis of class\nroom expenditures the average\namount available for each classroom\nwas approximately SI4OO. This *I4OO\nmust provide a teacher, janitorial ser\nvice, fuel to heat the classroom, books\nand instructional materials, admin\nistration and supervision, and all\nother current expenses for a year.\nUnlike the widow\u2019s oil, this *I4OO\ndoes not last indefinitely. Its elas\nticity is limited. As a result, class\nrooms are overcrowded and the\nteacher supply is inadequate. The\nchildren in Lincoln county are the\nlosers.\nNorth Carolina\u2019s financial effort\nto provide for public education has\nreached its limit. Over 70 per cent\nof the general fund appropriation is\nfor schools. The only hope for cor\nrecting this situation is a Federal\nappropriation for education.\nAs long ago as 1938, the report\nof President Roosevelt\u2019s advisory\ncommittee on education showed glar\ning inequalities of educational op\nportunity in the United States. Some\nstates were able to expand S6OOO for\neach classroom in contract to the\nSI4OO North Carolina provides. Since\nschool business is everybody\u2019s busi\nness every citizen in this county\nshould recognize the necessity for\nFederal Aid to Education.\nSchedule of Elections\nAAA Committeemen\nThe schedule for AAA committee\nmen elections in Lincoln county was\nannounced this week by the local\nAgricultural Adjustment Agency\ncommittee. The polling places, and\nthe dates and hours are as follows:\nRock Springs High School, Nov.\n30th\u20149 to 5.\nIron Station School, Nov. 30th\n9 t 0 5.\nCourthouse, Lincolnton, Nov. 30th\n9 to 5.\nHoward\u2019s Creek School. Nov. 30th\n\u20149 to 5.\nNorth Brook No. 2 School, Nov.\n30th\u20149 to 5.\nIf it is inconvenient for any fann\ner to go out in his own township to\nvote, he may come to the County of\nfice to do so.\nIn each community, farmers will\nelect three regular committeemen\nand two alternates. Elected at the\nsame time will be delegates to a\ncounty convention, to be held later,\nwhere a county committee will be\nelected for the coming year.\nThe AAA chairman said approxi\nmately 3,000 farmers are eligible to 1\ncast ballots in community elections.\nThis number includes all farmers who\nare cooperating in the agricultural\nconservation or crob insurance pro\ngrams.\nDiscussing the role of community\ncommitteemen, it was pointed out\nthat soil and water conservation will\ncontinue to loom large among AAA\nprogram objectives. Under the 1948 1\nACP Program, funds will be allocat- 1\ned to each county, and committeemen 1\nwill have more responsibility in help- 1\ning their neighbors to round out soil- 1\nbuilding plans for individual farms\nwithin the scope of approval prac- 1\ntices. This is only one of the pro\ngrams for which committeemen have\na great responsibility.\nWARNS TRAFFIC\nDEATHS MAY REACH\nALL-TIME RECORD\nChicago, Nov. 26\u2014A safety lighting\nexecutive predicted a yearly traffic\ntoll of 50,000 deaths and 1,750,000\ninjuries by 1950 unless causes of ac\ncidents are removed.\nA. F. Dickerson of Schenectady,\nN. Y., chairman of the International\nMunicipal Signal Association\u2019s street\nlighting committee, told the group\n\u201cit has been estimated that by 1950\ntraffic volumes in vehicle miles will\nbe increased from 50 to 100 per cent\nover 1941.\u201d\nDickerson said that installation of\nsafety lighting at dangerous intersec\ntions would reduce the number of\nnight traffic accidents, which he said\nwere now causing approximately two\ndeaths for every one in daylight\nhours.\nON LENOIR RHYNE HONOR ROLL\nMiss Mary Louise Warlick, stu\ndent at Lenoir Rhyne College, was\none of the eleven commercial stu\ndents who made the first Honor Roll\nfor the first quarter. Miss Warlick\nis the daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nHugh Warlick.\nTwo New Doctors\nAdded To Staff Os\nGamble Hospital\nSells Laundry Business\nfa\nW. A. Lilly (above), who for the\npast twenty-four years has owned\nand operated the Lincoln Steam\nLaundry, last week retired from the\nbusiness when he sold the plant to\nB. F. Staley, of Kannapolis. Mr. Lilly\ntold The Times that he has not yet\ndecided what business he will enter\nbut he expects to remain in Lincoln\nton. He and Mrs. Lilly have made\nmany friends during their residence\nhere who will be gratified that they\nwill continue to make their home\nhere.\nMRS. MAY JONES\nPASSES SUDDENLY\nFound Dead In Bed Friday\nMorning; Death Attributed\nto Heart Attack\nMrs. May Haynes Jones, 68, widow\nof L. B. Jones, was found dead in\nbed Friday morning at her home on\nthe Lincolnton and Maiden highway,\nabout three miles from Lincolnton.\nShe had apparently been in her usual\nhealth when she retired Thursday\nnight. Her death is ascribed to a\nheart attack.\nMrs. Jones was born in Lincoln\ncounty April 18, 1877, the daughter\nof the late John F. and Frances\nHartsoe Haynes.\nSurvivors are a step-son, Clarence\nJones; a step-daughter, Mrs. Lee\nHoover, of Newport News, Va.; three\nbrothers, J. H. Haynes, of Charlotte.\nForney Haynes, of Maiden, and S.\nHarbin Haynes, of Lincolnton.\nMrs. Jones was a devoted mem\nber of McKendree Methodist church\nfrom which funeral services will be\nconducted Tuesday afternoon at 2:30\no\u2019clock by the Rev. W. L. Harkey.\nBurial will be in the chcrch ceme-\ntery.\nMRS. H. P. CRAFT\nHURT IN WRECK\nMrs. H. P. Craft, of Cherryville,\nis in a serious condition in the Gor\ndon Crowell Memorial hospital as the\nresult of an automobile accident Sat\nurday night on the Cherryville-Pal\nlas highway, in Gaston county. Her\nchest was said to have been crushed\nand she was otherwise injured.\nAn ambulance from the Warlick\nFuneral Home, driven by Frank P.\nHeavner, went to the scene of the\nwreck to bring Mrs. Craft to Lin\ncolnton and en route back had a\nslight accident near Crouse, when\nthe ambulance failed to make a curve\nand lef tthe highway plunging into\nan open field.\nNone of the occupants of the am\nbulance, it was stated, were hurt\nthough the ambulance was damaged.\nCAN RE-FNLIST AS PFC\nMen honorably discharged from the\nArmy in the grade of private, who\nhave served as long as six months\nmay now be enlisted with the Reg\nular Army ratisg of Private First\nClass. 1\nRocky Ford Hatchery Named\nLincoln County Purina Dealers\nThe Rocky Ford Hatchery is an\nnouncing i n today\u2019s Times the com-'\nnany\u2019s appointment as Purina Deal\nrs in Lincoln county, succeeding the\nPolhill Feed Co. Associated with R. 1\nL. Ford in the management of the\nlew business will be his brother-in\naw, J. S. Boggs.\nThe Ford Hatchery recently began\nm enlargement program, extending\nthe plant through from Sycamore to\nPine street, which will give them am\nple room to take care of the Purina\nbusiness. The entire equipment of\nLincoln County's\nFavorite\nFamily\nNewspaper\nSINGLE COPY: FIVE CENTS\nI Dr. Charles W. Brown, Jr.,\nof Hamlet, and Dr. Rush E.\nNetterville, of U. S. Army,\nAre New Members.\nThe Reeves Gamble Hospital today\nannounced the addition of two new\nmembers to its staff. Dr. Charles W.\nBrown, Jr., of Hamlet, and Dr. Rush\nE. Netterville.\nDr. Brown, who has already ar\nrived i n Lincolnton, is a graduate\nof the Georgetown University School\nof Meoicine, class of 1941. He is\nunmarried.\nDr. Netterville, who will be tho\nchief surgeon, graduated in 1939\nfrom the Louisiana State University\nSchool of Medicine. He interned in\nthe'Charity Hospital in New Orleans\nin 1939 and 1940 and was resident\nphysician in Charity Hospital in\nPineville, La., 1940-41. He was in\nthe Medical Corps of the U. S. Army\nfrom June, 1941, to October, 1945.\nHe and his wife are expected to ar\nrive in Lincolnton Friday.\nDr. W. G. Bandy and Dr. Walter\nV. Costner, who were associated with\nthe late Dr. J. S. Gamble in the op\neration of the hospital, will remain\nas members of the staff.\nFarm Leaders Are\nNeeded In 4-H Work\nAll phases of 4-H activities are\nshowing great progress in the Wall\nburg community of Davidson county;\nand county and home agents of the\nState College Extension Service say\nthat thousands of such leaders as\nMrs. R. G. Lanning are needed\nthroughout the state.\nMrs. Lanning, the mother of a\nhome agent, has been a leader of\nHome Demonstration work for many\nyears and now she is specializing in\n4-H activities, helping other boys\nand girls do a better job.\nAccording to Lala Blalock, assist\nant home agent i n Davidson, Mrs.\nLanning has been president of the\ncounty Home Federation Council, a\nrepresentative to the State Council,\nand a willing neighborhood leader.\nThis fall she assisted with the Da\nvidson County Fair and was mado\ndirector of th e canning department.\nSo good was her own personal ex\nhibit from the 522 containers of food\nthat she prepared for her own fam\nily, that she won first prize at the\nfair. Later the same exhibit was\ncarried to the fall federation meet\ning at Lexington, where about X6O\nhome demonstration club women\nnoted her excellent standards of can\nning.\n\u201cMrs. Lanning is a very respon\nsible, dependable leader, who thor\noughly enjoys her activities,\u201d says\nMiss Blalock. \u201cShe is one of the\nmost outstanding home demonstra\ntion leaders that Davidson County\nhas produced, and we need thousands\nmore like her, both men and women,\nin all sections of North Carolina.\nGiven local leadership such as that\nsupplied by Mrs. Lanning, 4-H activ\nities can be greatly expanded and im\nproved. Her voluntary and unselfish\nleadership is a wonderful thing for\nthe boys and girls, who will be onr\nfarm leaders of tomorrow.\u201d\nReview Book Club\nHolds Nov. Meeting\nOne of the most enjoyable meet\nings of the Review Book Club wks\nheld Wednesday, November 21, with\nMrs. Floyd Cobb at her home on Oak\nstreet.\nMrs. Paul Mullen, president, pre\nsided and a short business session\nwas held.\nMrs. Leonard Wright gave the pro\ngram, the subject being, \u201cThe Life\nand Works of Robert Browning.\u201d\nDelicious refreshments were served\non card tables, carrying out the\nThanksgiving motif.\nOnly club members were present.\nSoldiers re-enlisting in the Army\nare paid a re-enlistment bonus of SSO\nfor each year of active service since\ntheir last entry into service.\ni the Polhill Feed Co. has been pur\nchased, which will facilitate tho\nhandling of the products.\nj Mr. Boggs stated today they will\ncarr y full lines of chicken, cow, dog,\ni turkey, pig and other feeds and they\nj invite the farmers and poultrymsn\ni from over the county to call oh them\nJI when in need of feeds.\n11 The Purina products are well\n.|know n and popular over the comity\nrand it will be good news that they\nt* r e to continue to b\u00ab sold hers.","height":"20640","width":"14892"}}
